A = {x | x is a set and x ∉ x}

In other words, A is the set of all sets x such that x is not an element of itself. Now, let's ask the question: is A an element of itself? If A is not an element of itself, then it should be included in the set A, since A contains all sets that are not members of themselves. But if A is an element of itself, then it should not be included in the set A, since A contains only sets that are not members of themselves. This creates a logical contradiction, and we have a paradox on our hands!

The set of all sets, on the other hand, is a more straightforward concept. We can define it as the union of all sets, denoted by:

U = ∪{x | x is a set}

This set contains all sets, including sets that contain themselves as elements. Note that U is not necessarily a set of sets that are not members of themselves, as some sets may contain themselves as elements. The key difference between the two sets is that A is self-referential, while U is not. A is trying to describe itself, which leads to the paradox, whereas U is simply a collection of all sets without any self-referential constraints.

